    <section id="evidence">
      <h2>What do the numbers actually say about B2B lead generation performance?</h2>
      <p>The headline metrics in B2B lead generation reveal a consistent pattern: most businesses generate enough leads — they convert too few of them, and they nurture almost none of them effectively.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>79% of marketing leads never convert to sales.</strong> The primary cause is inadequate lead nurturing — contacts are captured and then ignored until they go cold (<a href="https://www.marketingsherpa.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MarketingSherpa, 2023</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Only 27% of B2B leads generated by marketing are ever contacted by sales.</strong> Nearly three-quarters of captured leads receive zero follow-up (<a href="https://www.salesforce.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Salesforce, 2024</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Companies excelling at lead nurturing generate 50% more sales-ready leads at 33% lower cost</strong> — a compound advantage that builds over time (99Firms).</li>
        <li><strong>Companies with mature lead management processes report 133% more revenue</strong> than those with immature processes (<a href="https://www.forrester.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Forrester, 2023</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>B2B organisations that align sales and marketing achieve 24% faster revenue growth</strong> and 27% faster profit growth than those that don't (Forrester, 2023).</li>
        <li><strong>ABM programs see a 70% increase in pipeline value per targeted account</strong> (<a href="https://www.demandbase.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Demandbase, 2024</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Average B2B website conversion rate: 2.23%</strong> — meaning roughly 98 in 100 visitors leave without providing contact details (Power Digital).</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="ia-callout data">
        <strong>The gap that matters most:</strong> The difference between a B2B team generating leads and one generating revenue is almost always nurturing. A system that captures 100 leads and nurtures 80 of them outperforms one that captures 300 leads and nurtures none. The data on 79% of leads never converting reflects this gap directly.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="mistakes">
      <h2>What mistakes do B2B teams most commonly make with lead generation?</h2>
      <p>The same failure patterns appear repeatedly across B2B lead generation programmes, regardless of company size or industry.</p>
      <h3>1. Chasing volume instead of quality</h3>
      <p>61% of B2B marketers identify lead quality — not quantity — as their biggest challenge. Yet most teams measure success by leads generated per month, not by leads that eventually close. A lead volume metric with no quality filter rewards tactics that fill a CRM with contacts who will never buy.</p>
      <h3>2. No nurturing system</h3>
      <p>The 79% non-conversion statistic points directly here. Most B2B teams have a capture mechanism (a form, a landing page) but no systematic nurture sequence to engage contacts between capture and purchase readiness. Leads left alone go cold within days — then require expensive reactivation or are simply lost.</p>
      <h3>3. Slow or no follow-up on high-intent signals</h3>
      <p>Responding within 5 minutes of a high-intent action (demo request, pricing page visit, contact form) increases conversion probability by 9×. Yet 42% of sales reps report being too busy to follow up that quickly (InBeat Agency). The fix is usually a combination of prioritised queue management and automated initial outreach triggered by the action itself.</p>
      <h3>4. Single-channel dependency</h3>
      <p>Relying on one channel — most commonly LinkedIn outbound or cold email alone — creates pipeline fragility. When that channel's deliverability drops, a LinkedIn algorithm shifts, or a platform restricts automation, the entire pipeline stalls. A content plus email plus LinkedIn combination is the most resilient starting stack for most B2B businesses.</p>
      <h3>5. Sales and marketing misalignment</h3>
      <p>Only 41% of marketers report being completely satisfied with their multi-channel lead generation strategy (Salesforce / Warmly.ai). A significant share of that dissatisfaction traces to misaligned definitions: marketing calls a contact an MQL; sales disagrees and never calls them. Aligning on a shared definition of what constitutes a qualified lead before any tactics are deployed removes more pipeline friction than most software tools do.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="practice">
      <h2>What should you do with this in practice?</h2>
      <p>The research points to a sequence that works for most B2B teams and affiliate marketers building lead-dependent businesses, regardless of how the underlying offers are structured.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Start with ICP definition, not with channel selection.</strong> Write down specifically which job titles, company sizes, and industries describe your ideal buyers. Every channel and content decision follows from this. Without it, you optimize for clicks, not customers.</li>
        <li><strong>Pick two or three channels before expanding to six.</strong> The lowest-resistance starting stack for most businesses: SEO-driven content (lowest CPL, highest close rate), email nurture (lowest cost to maintain contact over a 10-month B2B cycle), and LinkedIn (for direct outreach and thought leadership). Add channels once each of these is generating measurable pipeline.</li>
        <li><strong>Build the nurture sequence before worrying about top-of-funnel volume.</strong> A contact captured without a follow-up plan loses most of its value within a week. Even a four-email sequence sent over 30 days outperforms no sequence by a significant margin on SQL conversion rate.</li>
        <li><strong>Measure cost per lead by channel.</strong> Compare your numbers against the benchmarks in the channel table above. If your SEO CPL is $120 but the benchmark is $31, you are either targeting high-competition keywords or converting traffic poorly — either is fixable once you can see the gap.</li>
        <li><strong>Set up an alert for high-intent signals and follow up within 5 minutes.</strong> Demo requests, pricing page visits, and trial sign-ups are high-intent moments. The 9× conversion advantage of a 5-minute response is one of the highest-ROI optimisations available to a B2B sales team and requires no additional spend.</li>
      </ol>
