    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions about B2B Lead Generation</h2>
      <div class="ia-faq">
        <details>
          <summary>What is the difference between a lead and a prospect in B2B?</summary>
          <p>A lead is anyone who has shown initial interest and provided contact details — they may or may not fit your ideal customer profile. A prospect is a lead that has been qualified: they match your target company size, industry, budget range, and decision-making authority. Not every lead becomes a prospect, which is why lead scoring and qualification are central to B2B lead generation.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How long does the average B2B sales cycle take?</summary>
          <p>The average B2B sales cycle runs approximately 10.1 months, compared to minutes or hours for most B2C purchases. Cycle length varies significantly by deal size and industry — software purchases often run 3–6 months, while enterprise contracts, regulated-industry deals, or purchases requiring legal review can stretch to 12–18 months or longer.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Which channels drive the highest-quality B2B leads?</summary>
          <p>According to Cvent, 73% of B2B marketers say webinars produce their best-quality leads. LinkedIn is the dominant social channel, driving approximately 80% of B2B social media leads. Organic search delivers leads that close at 14.6% — roughly 8.6 times the close rate of outbound leads at 1.7% (Search Engine Journal). The highest-quality channel for any given business depends on its ICP, average deal size, and content capability.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What is a good B2B lead conversion rate?</summary>
          <p>A conversion rate of 2–5% is generally considered good for B2B lead generation. The average B2B website converts at approximately 2.23% (Power Digital). Legal services leads all sectors at 7.4%, while B2B e-commerce converts at around 1.8%. What counts as "good" depends heavily on your industry, traffic quality, and how tightly you define a conversion.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What is the difference between an MQL and an SQL?</summary>
          <p>An MQL (Marketing-Qualified Lead) is a contact who has engaged with your marketing content enough to suggest buying intent — downloading a whitepaper, attending a webinar, or visiting a pricing page. An SQL (Sales-Qualified Lead) is a contact that the sales team has reviewed and confirmed as a real opportunity worth pursuing. Industry benchmarks show that only 12–18% of MQLs become SQLs (MarketJoy). The handoff between the two is one of the highest-friction points in B2B organisations.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How much does B2B lead generation cost?</summary>
          <p>Cost per lead varies significantly by channel. Organic SEO delivers the lowest average CPL at $31, followed by email ($53), webinars ($72), LinkedIn advertising ($75), and paid search ($110). Events and trade shows carry the highest average CPL at $811–$881 (DemandSage). The median B2B CPL across all channels sits at approximately $198–$214, with roughly 11% year-over-year inflation as of Q1 2026.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What is Account-Based Marketing (ABM) and how does it relate to B2B lead generation?</summary>
          <p>ABM is a targeted B2B strategy where sales and marketing teams align around a defined list of high-value accounts, rather than casting a wide net for individual leads. Instead of generating many leads and filtering down, ABM starts with the specific companies you want to win and builds personalised outreach toward the 6–9 decision-makers within each. Demandbase data shows ABM programs see a 70% increase in pipeline value per targeted account. ABM is most effective for businesses with high average contract values where the cost of highly targeted outreach is justified by deal size.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How is AI changing B2B lead generation?</summary>
          <p>AI has moved from a writing assistant into an active qualification and routing layer. In 2026, AI agents autonomously handle initial prospect research, data enrichment, lead scoring, and real-time routing, compressing speed-to-lead from hours to seconds. According to Forrester, AI-powered lead scoring improves conversion rates by approximately 30%. Businesses using AI for lead generation report 50% more sales-ready leads and 60% lower customer acquisition costs (InBeat Agency).</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

